body:
FIRRTL's inter-module constant propagation (IMCP) pass generates duplicate constants unnecessarily. These are naturally cleaned up by later common-subexpression elimination (CSE), but it seems cleaner to not do it this way.

Consider:

```mlir
module {
  firrtl.circuit "Foo"  {
    firrtl.module private @Bar(out %a: !firrtl.uint<1>, out %b: !firrtl.uint<1>) {
      %c1_ui1 = firrtl.constant 1 : !firrtl.uint<1>
      firrtl.strictconnect %a, %c1_ui1 : !firrtl.uint<1>
      firrtl.strictconnect %b, %c1_ui1 : !firrtl.uint<1>
    }
    firrtl.module @Foo(out %a: !firrtl.uint<1>, out %b: !firrtl.uint<1>) {
      %bar_a, %bar_b = firrtl.instance bar  @Bar(out a: !firrtl.uint<1>, out b: !firrtl.uint<1>)
      firrtl.strictconnect %a, %bar_a : !firrtl.uint<1>
      firrtl.strictconnect %b, %bar_a : !firrtl.uint<1>
    }
  }
}
```

This produces (`circt-opt -firrtl-imconstprop`) two copies of `firrtl.constant 1`:
```mlir
module {
  firrtl.circuit "Foo"  {
    firrtl.module private @Bar(out %a: !firrtl.uint<1>, out %b: !firrtl.uint<1>) {
      %c1_ui1 = firrtl.constant 1 : !firrtl.uint<1>
      firrtl.strictconnect %a, %c1_ui1 : !firrtl.uint<1>
      firrtl.strictconnect %b, %c1_ui1 : !firrtl.uint<1>
    }
    firrtl.module @Foo(out %a: !firrtl.uint<1>, out %b: !firrtl.uint<1>) {
      %c1_ui1 = firrtl.constant 1 : !firrtl.uint<1>
      %c1_ui1_0 = firrtl.constant 1 : !firrtl.uint<1>
      %bar_a, %bar_b = firrtl.instance bar  @Bar(out a: !firrtl.uint<1>, out b: !firrtl.uint<1>)
      firrtl.strictconnect %a, %c1_ui1 : !firrtl.uint<1>
      firrtl.strictconnect %b, %c1_ui1 : !firrtl.uint<1>
    }
  }
}
```

There may be a small performance improvement by caching known constants (either pre-existing or created) and using those instead of, assumedly, always creating a new constant. If the constant does not dominate the use, it would need to be moved (though I think constants are almost always declared at the top of each module).
